The Department of Education in KwaZulu-Natal, has expressed shock following death of a 10-year-old boy who was knocked by taxi on his way to school in Hambanathi area in Tongaat, on Tuesday morning. It is alleged that the taxi driver ran away after knocking down the pupil. Kwazi Mthethwa, provincial education department spokesperson, said they were devastasted to hear about the incident. He said: “On behalf of the department, we are very shocked by the accident that has claimed a child’s life. This accident happened at a very crucial time where pupils are writing their final examinations. We wish to convey our heartfelt condolences to the family who have lost a child from the horrible accident.” Paul Herbst, from IPSS Medical Rescue, said when paramedics arrived at the scene, the vehicle had fled. He said the pupil had succumbed to his injuries and that the 10-year-old was declared deceased at the scene of the accident. Herbst added: “It was later established that the taxi stopped a few metres away from the accident scene. This was due to members of the public wanting to assault the driver.” Captain Patrick Ngwane, Tongaat police spokesperson, confirmed the accident. He said: “Police are still on scene and a culpable homicide will be opened later.” Last month, the Waterloo community near Verulam took the law into their own hands when a man ran over and killed a 10-year-old boy. Tabloid Media, reported that the man was allegedly speeding when he lost control of his bakkie and knocked down the boy, who was playing on the side of the road. He sped off and crashed into a boundary fence. He was then attacked and seriously injured by community members. The boy died on scene.